    "---\n",
    "## 9. Reflective Question\n",
    "\n",
    "### *"When is feature engineering a nice-to-have, and when is it a must-have?"*\n",
    "\n",
    "**Nice-to-have:** When your model is already a powerful learner (e.g., a deep neural net or gradient-boosted tree with many features), the algorithm can often discover non-linear relationships on its own. Adding engineered features *may* give a small lift, but the raw data is often sufficient.  \n",
    "\n",
    "**Must-have:** \n",
    "1. **Linear models** — logistic regression or linear SVM can only learn from linear combinations. Encoding domain knowledge through ratios, bins, or polynomial features is the only way to capture non-linearity.\n",
    "2. **Small datasets** — with limited examples, injecting domain knowledge via engineered features compensates for what the model can't learn from data alone.\n",
    "3. **Sparse or categorical domains** — raw text, raw timestamps, or category IDs carry almost no signal until transformed (TF-IDF, cyclic encoding, interaction terms).\n",
    "4. **Interpretability requirements** — stakeholders often need features that map directly to business concepts (e.g., *age_when_added*, *cast_size*) rather than opaque model weights.\n",
    "\n",
    "In this Netflix dataset, `duration_value` was already available — but `age_when_added`, `era`, and `log_duration` turned out to contribute real signal (as confirmed by Mutual Information). Without those transformations, a linear classifier would have struggled with the right-skewed raw duration. → **Here it was a must-have for model quality, and a nice-to-have for interpretability.**"
   ]
